-- A skolem introduced under an inner `forall` must not escape into an outer
-- existential. Checking `\(y) -> x` against `forall a. (a) -> a` makes `a`
-- rigid, so the body `x` would have to be that rigid `a`; but `x` is `bad`'s
-- parameter, whose type is fixed outside the quantifier. Solving it to `a`
-- would let the skolem escape, so the call is rejected here, at `useid(...)`,
-- not at the later use of `x`.
fn useid(g : forall a. (a) -> a) : Int = g(10)

fn bad(x) =
  useid(\(y) -> x)
  x
